# Development Architecture Context

- Apply SOLID principles in design and implementation.
- Apply Hexagonal Architecture (Ports and Adapters).
- Apply CQRS where command and query responsibilities are clearly separated.
- Use CQRS without Event Sourcing by default for this application.
- Use immutable entities in the write side only.

## Atomicity of CQRS Artifacts

- Each command, event, and handler must represent a single, focused intent.
- A command file must contain one command schema and one derived type — never bundle multiple commands in one file.
- A handler file must handle exactly one command or one event.
- Commands and handlers are atomic by default; use one focused business intent per command and one handler per command or event type.
- A combined create/update use case is allowed only when the caller contract is explicitly upsert-like. In that case, use `Upsert{Aggregate}...` or `CreateOrUpdate{Aggregate}...` naming.
- Batch-processing handlers are allowed, but their names must include `Bulk`. The corresponding command name should also include `Bulk`.
- `Save*`, `Manage*`, and other catch-all command or handler names are forbidden when they hide the real business intent.
- When renaming a command, event, or handler: rename the file, the schema, and the type together as a single atomic operation.
- The filename must always match the schema and type name it contains (e.g., `UserUpdateDisplayNameCommand.ts` → `UserUpdateDisplayNameSchema` + `UserUpdateDisplayName` type).
- Use SQL storage for both write model and outbox in the same database schema.
- Persist write model changes and outbox records in one transactional operation.

## Ports and Adapters Naming Rules

- Use case files must use the `<Name>.usecase.ts` naming pattern (example: `CreateCronjobK8s.usecase.ts`).
- Port contracts must use the `I*.port.ts` naming pattern.
- Adapter implementations must use the `*.adapter.ts` naming pattern.
- Keep adapters in infrastructure-facing layers and keep ports in application/domain-facing layers.

## Grouping Ports in Method Signatures

- When a method requires one or more ports, always group them into a single `ports` object parameter.
- This rule applies to static factories, command handlers, domain services, and entity methods.
- Apply this rule even for a single port.
- Keep business input data in `params` and infrastructure dependencies in `ports`.

```ts
// ✅ multiple ports
static async create(
	params: CreateConfigSnapshotParams,
	ports: {
		uuidPort: UuidPort;
		dateTimePort: DateTimePort;
		categoryRepository: CiConfigTypeRepository;
	},
): Promise<ConfigSnapshot> {
	const { uuidPort, dateTimePort, categoryRepository } = ports;
	// ...
}

// ✅ single port
delete(ports: { dateTimePort: DateTimePort }): void {
	const { dateTimePort } = ports;
	// ...
}
```
